When unclear, check the most recent `session_last.md` in `~/.claude/projects/-Users-bflanary*/memory/` — it should declare which machine the work was done on.

## Switching Machines Procedure

1. **Wrap up the current machine** — commit + push everything, write a `session_last.md` entry to the project's memory folder.
2. **Move to the other machine** — `git pull` the relevant repo(s) + `~/.claude`.
3. **If you need state that isn't in git** — see "Ad-hoc state sync" below.
4. **Driving the canonical machine remotely** —
   ```
   ssh main             # or `ssh mini`
   tmux new -s pipeline # first time, or `tmux attach -t pipeline` to rejoin
   # ... do work ...
   # Ctrl-b d to detach. Work survives the SSH disconnect.
   ```

## Playlist Rotation Rule (Critical)

YT pipelines run **only on main**. `~/.yt_playlist_rotation.json` is main-local state and is NOT synced. Running a YT pipeline on mini while main is also active produces duplicate playlist inserts.

To drive a YT pipeline from mini: `ssh main` and trigger it on main. Do not run YT-pipeline launchd plists on mini.

If multi-machine YT rotation ever becomes a real need, a Phase 3 plan must move `~/.yt_playlist_rotation.json` to git or a shared store with lock semantics.

## Ad-hoc State Sync

State files (gcloud creds, YT tokens, metrics.db, work_dirs) are NOT in git and NOT auto-synced between machines. When you need them on the other machine, use rsync:

```bash
# gcloud creds (after a fresh `gcloud auth login` on main)
rsync -av main:~/.config/gcloud/ ~/.config/gcloud/

# YT OAuth tokens
rsync -av main:~/.yt_tokens/ ~/.yt_tokens/

# Pull main's metrics.db to a read-only mirror on mini (for dashboard inspection)
rsync -av main:~/.ops_metrics/metrics.db ~/.ops_metrics/metrics_main.db

# Inspect a specific work_dir
rsync -av main:~/Projects/youtube-automation/work/<channel>/<run_id>/ /tmp/inspect-<run_id>/
```

Phase 2 will wrap these in `~/Projects/AI-Crew/scripts/sync/` helpers.

## Sudo Convenience

Each machine has a narrow NOPASSWD sudoers entry at `/etc/sudoers.d/<user>` covering tailscale CLI, `brew services`, `kill`, `rm`, `cp`, `mv`, `launchctl`, `systemextensionsctl`. Anything outside that list still prompts.

Audit/add to scope: `sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/<user>`. Validate with `visudo -c` before saving.

## Tailscale Daemon — Reminders

- Tailscale on these machines is the **CLI build** (`brew install tailscale`), NOT the sandboxed GUI / Mac App Store version.
- The brew service is `homebrew.mxcl.tailscale` (LaunchDaemon at `/Library/LaunchDaemons/`).
- Logs: `/opt/homebrew/var/log/tailscaled.log`.
- Re-auth: `sudo /opt/homebrew/opt/tailscale/bin/tailscale up --ssh --accept-routes`.
- Status: `tailscale status`.
- If the sandboxed `macsys` system extension is somehow re-enabled, it will steal `/var/run/tailscaled.socket` and SSH will silently break. Toggle it off in System Settings → General → Login Items & Extensions → Network Extensions, then `kill` the sysext daemon process, then `sudo brew services restart tailscale`.

## Verification Checklist (Phase 1)

- [ ] `ssh main` from mini connects without password.
- [ ] `ssh mini` from main connects without password.
- [ ] `tailscale debug prefs` on each machine shows `"RunSSH": true`.
- [ ] `tmux` survives a disconnect end-to-end.
- [ ] `~/.claude/rules/cross-machine.md` (this file) is reachable on both machines after `git pull` of `~/.claude`.


# diagrams

# Diagrams / Drawings

When asked for a diagram, drawing, architecture diagram, flowchart, system map, or "draw me ...":

**Standard: modern, dark-mode, exported to PDF (+ PNG for inline preview). NEVER use mermaid — Brad considers it ugly/not modern.**

## Tool choice
- **Default → D2** (`d2`): text → polished dark diagram, native PDF+PNG.
- **Icon-rich cloud/infra → mingrammer `diagrams`** (Python; interpreter `~/.diagram-tools/venv/bin/python`, needs Graphviz `dot`).
- **Fully bespoke visual → hand-authored SVG → `rsvg-convert`**.

## Output convention
Write into the project's `diagrams/` folder. Produce `<name>.pdf` (primary, dark) + `<name>.png` (inline preview) + keep the source (`.d2`/`.py`/`.svg`). In markdown: embed PNG, link PDF.

## Commands
```bash
# D2 (default) — dark themes: 200 Dark Mauve, 201 Dark Flagship Terrastruct
d2 --theme 200 --pad 40 diagrams/<name>.d2 diagrams/<name>.pdf
d2 --theme 200 --pad 40 diagrams/<name>.d2 diagrams/<name>.png

# mingrammer diagrams — set graph_attr bgcolor "#0b0f17" + light fontcolor for dark mode
~/.diagram-tools/venv/bin/python diagrams/<name>.py   # Diagram(..., outformat=["pdf","png"])

# bespoke SVG → PDF/PNG
rsvg-convert -f pdf -o diagrams/<name>.pdf diagrams/<name>.svg
rsvg-convert -f png -z 2 -o diagrams/<name>.png diagrams/<name>.svg
```

Claude Code: a richer `/diagram` skill exists at `~/.claude/skills/diagram/`. Always read the rendered PNG back to self-check (overlaps, legibility, dark mode) before reporting done.


